<!-- Node: "Merger: Rust and Inside3D" -->
<div class="body_box_header">Merger: Rust and Inside3D</div>
<div class="body_box"><small>Submitted by <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/view/2" title="View user profile.">Gard</a> on Tuesday, March 9, 2004 - 02:39</small><br /><br />
<p>Today, <i>Gard</i> made RUST history by suggesting a merger with <a href="http://www.inside3d.com">Inside3d</a> one of the leading game programming web sites on the Internet. <i>Gard</i> said,</p>

<font color=red>
<blockquote>
"Inside3d is one of the best programming websites on the internet, predominantly they are a Quake and Quake II programming website but a lot of their core users have experience with HalfLife, Quake III and Jedi Knights. If Inside3d was to merge with Rust, their addition would complement RUST. Both websites would win, as the resource base, tutorials, users, articles would double/tripple over night. This would immediately re-energies both websites"
</blockquote>
</font>

<p><i>Gard's</i> original suggestion to Inside3d can be viewed on the <a href="http://forums.inside3d.com/showflat.pl?Board=Inside3D&Number=17552&page=0&view=collapsed&sb=5">Inside3d Forum Post</a> and similar post was simulataneously posted on the <a href="http://forums.gamedesign.net/viewtopic.php?p=42380#42380">RUST Forums</a>.
<br /><br />
<a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/login" >Login</a> or <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/register" >Register</a> to post comments &middot; <a href="http://assets.aq2world.com/archive/websites/www.gamedesign.net/node/view/198" title="Read the rest of this posting." class="read-more"><b>Read more</b></a>
</div><br />


<!-- Node: "Clan Recruiter" -->
<div class="body_box_header">Clan Recruiter</div>
<div class="body_box"><small>Submitted by <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/view/1804" title="View user profile.">Kingpin_Xatrix</a> on Monday, March 8, 2004 - 22:12</small><br /><br />
For those of you who want to join clan or recruit players for your clan you can visit <a href = "http://www.clanrecruiter.net/index.php">Clan Recruiter</a>.<br><br>

So, what is <b>Clan Recruiter</b>? Well in online and LAN games, players group together in teams called ‘clans’. Clan Recruiter is a website that helps clans to find players and players to find clans. Currently, clans recruiting players have to use forums, in-game chat and word of mouth, which is hardly ideal. Clan Recruiter changes this by providing a central place where clans can go to list themselves and find available players, while free players can pick a clan that suits them. Clan Recruiter is all about communication and community building within an accessible, user friendly website.
<br /><br />
<a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/login" >Login</a> or <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/register" >Register</a> to post comments &middot; <a href="http://assets.aq2world.com/archive/websites/www.gamedesign.net/node/view/197" title="Read the rest of this posting." class="read-more"><b>Read more</b></a>
</div><br />


<!-- Node: "Nvidia Doom3 benchmark" -->
<div class="body_box_header">Nvidia Doom3 benchmark</div>
<div class="body_box"><small>Submitted by <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/view/1804" title="View user profile.">Kingpin_Xatrix</a> on Sunday, March 7, 2004 - 04:03</small><br /><br />
There's a rumour that <a href = "http://www.nvidia.com">Nvidia</a>, before release of Doom3, will have a benchmark utility on their website. Utility will test your pc, to see how fast it is going to run Doom3.
<br><br>
You can also find benchmark <a href ="http://www.hardocp.com/article.html?art=NDc0">here</a>. The author of that article thanks John Carmack, Tim Willits (Id Software) and Jim Black (Nvidia) for their great help with the testing. John Carmack, described the demo they used for testing as a random code drop from a recent build of Doom3 and he believes it to be representative of
<br /><br />
